question:
Suppose that $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
2 & 0 & -1 \\ 
3 & 1 & 0 \\ 
-2 & 1 & 3 \end{array}
\right)$.

Find matrix $B$ such that matrices $A$ and $B$ are inverses.

Consider $A=\left( \begin{array}{rr}
1 & 1 \\ 
0 & 1 \end{array}
\right)$ and  $B=\left( \begin{array}{rr}
a & b \\ 
c & d \end{array}
\right)$. If $A$ commutes with $B$, (AB = BA) then which of the following statements is correct?

answer1:
$\left| \begin{array}{rrr}
a & b & c \\ 
a & b & c \\ 
d & e & f \end{array}
\right|=0 $

answer2:
$\left| \begin{array}{rrr}
a & b & c \\ 
-d & -e & -f \\ 
g & h & i \end{array}
\right|=\left| \begin{array}{rrr}
a & b & c \\ 
d & e & f \\ 
g & h & i \end{array}
\right|$

answer3:
$\left| \begin{array}{rrr}
a & b & c \\ 
d & e & f \\ 
g & h & i \end{array}
\right|=-\left| \begin{array}{rrr}
a & d & g \\ 
b & e & h \\ 
c & f & i \end{array}
\right|$

